**Please expand on a research idea you are most interested in working on. It could be from the list I have posted or your own idea (~250 words)**

I'm particularly interested in exploring how we can induce Large Language Model (LLM) based agents to act in a Pareto optimal manner within multi-agent systems. This research direction aligns with the broader goal of understanding emergent cooperation between self-interested AI agents and has significant implications for developing more efficient and ethically-aligned AI systems. My proposed study would focus on:

1. Developing a framework for evaluating Pareto optimality in LLM-based multi-agent interactions
2. Designing and implementing mechanisms to encourage Pareto optimal decision-making in LLMs
3. Analyzing the emergence of cooperative behaviors as a result of pursuing Pareto optimal outcomes
4. Comparing the results with classical findings in open-source game theory

Key research questions would include:

- How can we effectively represent and optimize for Pareto optimality in the context of LLM decision-making?
- What techniques (e.g., multi-objective optimization, preference adaptation) are most effective in guiding LLMs towards Pareto optimal behaviors?
- How does the pursuit of Pareto optimality affect the evolution of agent strategies over time?
- Can we observe the emergence of sophisticated cooperative strategies as a result of optimizing for Pareto efficiency?

This research could provide valuable insights into creating more cooperative and efficient AI systems, potentially informing the design of future multi-agent AI architectures that balance individual and collective interests more effectively.

In my recent project, "View From Above: A Framework for Evaluating Distribution Shifts in LLMs," I, along with my co-authors, introduce a evaluation method for assessing out-of-distribution bias in large language models (LLMs) in a robust and domain-agnostic manner. This is done by, firstly, constructing a well-defined environment such that the model has an element of influence over the state of the environment (e.g. switch, card draw). All environments created are located under the environments folder of the repository (refer to deception/environments/blackjack.py for environment definition). After this, the model does 1000+ trials in the aforementioned environment where, for each trial, we collect the action outcomes of the model. Prompts for the model are located in deception/pyfiles/prompt.py. These experiments are performed in deception/main.py (for local API-call based inferences) and deception/multivac.ipynb (for opensource results inferencing due to using Vast.ai). All results from the experiments are then saved in deception/results directory. After this we perform statistical tests (i.e. chi-square, anderson-darling) for distribution shifts, comparing the distribution of LLM-generated action outcomes to that of desired action outcomes. These statistical tests are defined in deception/pyfiles/statistical_analysis.py). As an initial proof-of-concept we apply this framework to the game of blackjack and found that there is statistical evidence that models are misaligned with the expected game goal of fairness. Refer to the paper for more detailed information.

Over the summer I interned at Epirus, a company developing directed energy systems for defending against drone attacks. My project was to design a reinforcement learning agent to engage unknown swarms of drones in a simulation using waveforms, where the effectiveness of any given waveform was unknown. Since the action and observation spaces were dynamic (as drones were disabled), I implemented action masking in PyTorch to handle this, so that the agent only selected valid actions. Because of this and other small optimizations I made, I ended up implementing Proximal Policy Optimization from scratch in PyTorch. This was both very fulfilling and deeply frustrating at times. I also developed a custom simulation environment as part of this. The main challenge was making the simulation fast while making it as physically realistic as possible. NumPy was very helpful for this, and treating drones observations as a matrix of vectors made things easier. For visualization and debugging purposes, I also rendered the simulation using OpenGL to see the agent in real-time.

My introduction to AI Safety was through a course I took in Fall 2023 at Georgia Tech called AI Ethics and Policy, which discussed the ethical implications of AI in modern society. In the aforementioned class we read The Alignment Problem by Brian Christian discussing the book as we went with regard to AI methodology and policy creation to handle cases like COMPAS. Furthermore as apart of the class, we were tasked with exploring, designing and justifying a set of policies to regulate a specific area and usage of AI. My team and I focused on the usage of generative AI in politics where I mainly focused on the final section (design of policies). You can find our paper here: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1aJN2wWqNUPOQ5fpRIXdIeXLujUSRG-BE/view?usp=drivesdk. Throughout the class, I began to realize that ever since I first got into AI, I’ve always been interested in AI safety but I just never knew the outlet and field I could express it through. Knowing that this was the field I was interested in, I continued to read more AI Safety books like Superintelligence by Nick Bostrom and Human Compatible by Stuart Russell. In addition to this, I decided to explore the field of mechanistic interpretability. So far, I’ve focused on building up the foundations and reading seminal papers and findings within the field. Such papers include those on the transformer-circuits.pub blog by Anthropic as well as those recommended by Neel Nanda in this document: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1HnpLcU0wlyUzRn6e8lCVFpPmKeh8tj9YrYz_ToMFY-w/edit. As supplementary to this, I have also begun working through the ARENA course material in my spare time (currently finished modules 0 and 1 and on module 2) so that I can begin my own investigations and get a more formal understanding of the subject matter.
